The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, April 28, 2003  Business Briefs New Delhi, April 27: Maruti Udyog  will be developed as a research and development (R amp;D)  hub for the entire Asian market by Suzuki Motor Corporation.  This plan was revealed in the draft prospectus filed by  Maruti with the Securities and Exchange Board of India to  divest 25 per cent government stake through a public issue.  With this, the countrys largest carmaker would become the  only R amp;D centre for cars outside Japan for Suzuki.  Dahej (Gujarat), April 27: Petronet  LNG will sign next month an agreement with Indian Oil Corp,  Bharat Petroleum Corp and Gas Authority of India for committed  offtake of imported LNG, which it proposes to market before  the end of current fiscal. Bangalore, April 27: The Indian  subsidiary of Nortel Networks will focus on providing solutions  in contact centre, security, voice over internet protocol  and metro area network segments to enterprises through channel  partners and distributors. New Delhi, April 27: The Universal  Service Obligation Fund, set up last year to compensate  telecom operators for meeting non-profitable ventures like  rural telephony, will invite bids for replacement of two  lakh village public telephones by July this year. New Delhi, April 27: The standing  committee on finance, headed by N. Janardhana Reddy, has  suggested that penalties be imposed on public and private  sector banks that register shortfalls in lending to agriculture.  It has also recommended abolition of interests on Rural  Infrastructure Development Fund.
